DHT11 Temperature and Humidity Sensor

This project reads temperature and humidity using a DHT11 sensor and prints the values to the Serial Monitor.
It helps beginners understand how to interface environmental sensors with Arduino.

This project helps beginners learn:
-Using the DHT11 sensor with Arduino
-Reading temperature and humidity values
-Using the DHT library
-Displaying sensor data via Serial Monitor

Arduino Code
#include <DHT.h>
#include <DHT_U.h>

#define Type DHT11
int sensePin = 2;
float Temperature;
float Humidity;
int dts = 500;
int dt = 1000;

DHT HT(sensePin, Type);

void setup() {
  Serial.begin(9600);
  HT.begin();
  delay(dts);
}

void loop() {
  // Read temperature and humidity
  Temperature = HT.readTemperature();
  Humidity = HT.readHumidity();

  // Print values to Serial Monitor
  Serial.print(Temperature);
  Serial.print("°    ");
  Serial.print(Humidity);
  Serial.println("%");

  delay(dt);
}

Circuit Setup

Components needed:
Arduino Uno (or compatible board)
1 × DHT11 sensor
1 × 10kΩ resistor (if required by your DHT11 module)
Breadboard
Jumper wires

Wiring Instructions:

DHT11 Sensor
Data → pin 2
VCC → 5V
GND → GND
Pull-up resistor (10kΩ) between VCC and Data if using a bare DHT11

How it works:
The DHT11 sensor measures temperature and humidity.
The DHT library handles communication with the sensor.
Serial Monitor prints temperature in Celsius and humidity percentage every second.
